tics, and morality, the book explores how the use of oil money to fund the revolution's social programs and political reforms produced profound cultural anxieties about the contaminating effects of petroleum revenues in everyday settings. Tracing how these anxieties rippled out into community life, family networks, and local politics, Wilde shows how questions about how to live a good life came to be intimately shaped by Venezuela's contradictory relationship with oil. In doing so, he brings a vital perspective to contemporary debates about energy transitions by proposing a new way of thinking about the political and moral economies of natural resources in postcolonial settings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPetroleum industry and tradexGovernment policyzVenezuela2DLC. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexMoral and ethical aspectszVenezuela2DLC. 0aWorking classzVenezuelazValencia (Carabobo)2DLC. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aBolivarian Revolution.  aLatin America.  aVenezuela.  amorality.  aoil.  apolitics.  aurban life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363708540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637085423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637085/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles